    "id": 19,
    "category": "Compliance & Regulatory",
    "company": "Regulation: FedRAMP 20x",
    "summary": "FedRAMP launched its 20x modernization program in March 2025, replacing static documentation packages with continuous, machine-readable Key Security Indicators (KSIs). Phase 2 wrapped up in early 2026, with wide-scale adoption of Low and Moderate authorizations projected for Q3–Q4 2026. RFC-0024 (proposed January 2026) requires all Rev5 FedRAMP providers to produce OSCAL machine-readable authorization packages by September 30, 2026, or risk certification revocation by September 30, 2027. Federal agencies must now prefer FedRAMP-authorized cloud video platforms or accept increased audit risk. The new path also allows SOC 2 Type II to be leveraged as a temporary FedRAMP Validated designation, creating an opportunity for vendors with both credentials.",
    "source_url": "https://www.fedramp.gov/20x/",
    "why_vbrick": "Vbrick holds FedRAMP authorization and FIPS 140-2 certification, making it directly eligible under both the legacy Rev5 path and the SOC 2-leveraged FedRAMP Validated pathway. As agencies scramble to audit their cloud video stacks for FedRAMP compliance ahead of the September 2026 OSCAL deadline, Vbrick's existing authorization is a procurement differentiator that eliminates months of agency risk analysis.",
    "outreach_angle": "Lead with the September 2026 OSCAL machine-readable package deadline: frame it as a procurement gate — agencies that rely on non-FedRAMP-authorized video platforms will face contract disruption during their next authorization cycle. Offer a 30-minute audit readiness review showing how Vbrick's FedRAMP Moderate authorization maps to existing agency ATOs, eliminating compliance risk before the deadline.",
    "target_persona": "Federal IT Director, Agency CISO, Contracting Officer",
    "industry": "Federal Government",
