    "id": 20,
    "category": "Compliance & Regulatory",
    "company": "Regulation: FedRAMP Rev5 OSCAL Deadline",
    "summary": "RFC-0024, proposed January 2026 and closing for comment March 11, 2026, mandates that all FedRAMP Rev5 cloud service providers produce machine-readable OSCAL authorization packages by September 30, 2026 (initial deadline) and September 30, 2027 (final deadline). Failure to comply by the final deadline results in FedRAMP certification revocation. This creates a hard procurement gate: agencies cannot award contracts to CSPs that lose FedRAMP status. Cloud video platforms used by federal agencies that are not currently FedRAMP-authorized face immediate replacement pressure as agencies conduct their ICT supply-chain compliance reviews.",
    "source_url": "https://www.governmentcontractslegalforum.com/2026/01/articles/government-contracts/fedramp-proposes-updates-to-authorization-process-six-new-rfcs-released-for-public-comment/",
    "why_vbrick": "Vbrick's FedRAMP authorization and FIPS 140-2 compliance means it is already in the authorized ecosystem and will transition to machine-readable packaging as required. Agencies that currently use non-FedRAMP video platforms (e.g., commercial streaming tools, unapproved collaboration tools) face a hard swap decision by 2026. Vbrick is the ready alternative with no procurement delay.",
    "outreach_angle": "Send a one-page compliance brief to agency IT procurement teams explaining the September 2026 OSCAL deadline and its implications for non-authorized video vendors. Position Vbrick as the only enterprise video platform that removes this risk today. Offer a complimentary compliance mapping document showing how Vbrick's FedRAMP package aligns to their existing system boundary.",
