    "category": "Compliance & Regulatory",
    "company": "Regulation: EU AI Act — AI Note-Taking & Video Transcription",
    "summary": "Eprivacy EU's April 2025 guidance and LinkedIn enforcement discussion confirm that AI tools recording and transcribing video meetings process personal data — including names, IP addresses, voiceprints, and emotional signals — making the enterprise the GDPR controller. If the AI tool analyzes emotion or sentiment from video, it could qualify as a prohibited practice or high-risk AI under the EU AI Act. Transparency obligations under Article 50 of the EU AI Act already require disclosure when meeting participants interact with AI systems, and that AI-generated content (transcripts/summaries) be labeled as such. AI literacy obligations for staff using AI transcription tools are already in force as of February 2025.",
    "source_url": "https://blog.eprivacy.eu/?p=2329",
    "why_vbrick": "Vbrick's AI transcription generates clearly labeled AI-generated content, provides participant disclosure workflows before recording begins, maintains logs of AI processing for regulatory audit, and does not perform prohibited emotion recognition analytics — satisfying both the current GPAI transparency requirements (in force since August 2025) and the high-risk AI obligations approaching in August 2026.",
    "outreach_angle": "Target European enterprise customers: 'AI literacy requirements for staff using AI transcription tools have been mandatory since February 2025. Has your organization completed AI Act training for employees using Copilot, Otter.ai, or embedded Teams transcription?' Position Vbrick as the governance-ready alternative: purpose-built disclosure workflows, labeled AI outputs, and documentation that satisfies EU AI Act deployer obligations.",
